Just because the top 6 have fallen off, doesnt mean the league is weaker. It means the opposite in my opinion. Lower Teams have so much more money now that they dont have to sell their players whenever an offer comes in. 8 years ago I would bet money that James Maddison, Adama Traore and Jack Grealish are sold in the winter window, probably too the top 6. But now the lower teams can tell the bigger ones to stuff it.
The league is more balanced than if has been in generations, that doesnt mean its weaker.

Also please just put some respect on Livsrpools name, when City walked the league in 2017/18 everyone was on the pep koolade, but that team would be 5 points behind us this year.

snippet.textDisplay: Its all to do with the money these clubs get now in the Premier league. 10 - 15 years ago it was a 4 hours race with the occasional 5th due these clubs having all the money, facilities, scouts all around the world, top managers. However I think this all changed when Leicester won the league it showed everyone else it's possible if you spend write and have a well run team to beat the so called top 4. You could say Man U , Chelsea, arsenal, Tottenham are not once what they were however I believe the transfer market is to blame for this. Players who once would of gone for 20mil are now being brought for 80 in the hopes they become a superstar.  But you see the smaller teams making smarter decisions finding rough diamonds and onces that suit there squad as there scouts, and facilities to sort out these players has become world wide as they have the money now. This is by far the best league due to the competitive ability of every team to beat another from top to bottom taking out Liverpool.

snippet.textDisplay:
The league is weaker this year, down to every team apart from Liverpool being so inconsistent.
Liverpool have taken it to a new level this year by being consistent week in week out. I’d arguably say they played much better football last year.

City have lost to wolves x2, Norwich - no disrespect to either of them clubs, nobody would have given them a hope in hells chance 9/10. They lost to united and Liverpool, which can happen any season.

Spurs were in a CL final in June, an if you said to any spurs fan that by Xmas they would have sacked MP and replaced him with Jose, they would want some of what you had been smoking.
Arsenal have been up and down for a few seasons, Chelsea too and united look a shadow of the club they’ve been for 25 years.
The rest of the league is a much of a muchness, it’s just Leicester who’ve got a way of playing under their manager, with a good squad of players who have broken into the top 4 so far; but if you had said in the summer that Leicester would have spent x amount of months in the top 4 so far this season you would have been laughed at.

I can honestly say the league is weaker, but credit where it’s due to Liverpool for showing they are able to handle pressure; an whatever team they put out the professionalism that they have amongst their squad, that the level of quality doesn’t drop.

Liverpool aside, the league is as up and down as the championship has been this season.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm loving how Rory is arguing with his own point throughout half of this. He is saying you can't blame the managers for a players form which is partly true both the player and manager will effect a players form. But he is also saying that Chelsea's midfield is better than Liverpool's on paper which is probably true, but as a team it doesn't work and add up to that. As a team the most important thing is system and how the players work within that (best example is probably Sheffield who have a very good system for the players in their team, they don't have world class players but are performing at a much higher level than they should on paper). The system is made by the manager and the coaching so surely if a team is playing badly for a prolonged period and across multiple players form is bad then you surely can't just blame the players its surely most likely to be a coaching issue. The premier League is going through a period where the majority of the big clubs are having a crisis of identity where they are changing and aren't recovering, which as allowing the smaller clubs who have less to change in their infrastructure and less cost to change to capitalise. The big clubs are struggling because they can't make the big managerial acquisitions at the moment because the previously world class managers are retiring or have been figured out and so aren't as good. And now ex players are being put in the managerial role and for a while the performance will be bad as clubs interchange this new generation of managers until they find the right fit for the club's identity and profile. Once that is done the premier league will most likely be back to where it 'should' be

snippet.textDisplay: This whole debate is really stupid and daft. The Premier League has been in decline for the last decade. It hasnt been the same since Fergie retired. The standards dropped after Fergie retired. Saying that Liverpool are miles ahead because everyone else is weak is daft. Liverpool are exposing the true level of the Premier League. After Fergies retirement the Premier League has been the most toxic inconsistent League in the world, overinflated with 2nd tier foreign players. The main reason is because the teams don't spend wisely, they don't spend on developing English youth and just focus on short term solutions. I also think money has ruined the game overall not just in the Premier League but in every League in the world. Because even when young players do breakthrough they get ridculous contracts with huge wages and they just lose motivation and hunger. Liverpool is the only team exempt from this. Football has turned into a business and thats why the Premier League teams are "badly coached" because the players and owners and managers treat it as a business and not a game. Again Liverpool and City are exempt from this. Liverpool because they have a passionate manager who loves football and City because they have an owner who actually cares about Football.
